nodes.label: Geometric Constructions
nodes.title: The process of drawing geometric shapes, angles, and figures accurately using only specific tools such as a compass and straightedge.

nodes.label: Circle Construction with Given Radius
nodes.title: Drawing a circle with a specified radius using a compass.

nodes.label: Use of Compass
nodes.title: Using a compass to draw circles and arcs or to transfer distances.

nodes.label: Use of Straightedge
nodes.title: Employing a straightedge (unmarked ruler) to draw straight lines between points.

nodes.label: Use of Ruler
nodes.title: Using a ruler to measure and draw straight lines of specific lengths.

nodes.label: Use of Protractor
nodes.title: Using a protractor to measure and construct angles.

nodes.label: Use of Set Square
nodes.title: Using a set square to draw right angles and other specific angles.

nodes.label: Dynamic Geometry Software
nodes.title: Software tools that allow the creation and manipulation of geometric constructions digitally.

nodes.label: Application of Constructions in Real-Life Contexts
nodes.title: Using geometric constructions to solve practical problems encountered in everyday life.

nodes.label: Cartesian plane
nodes.title: A two-dimensional plane defined by a horizontal axis (x-axis) and a vertical axis (y-axis) used to plot points, lines, and curves.

nodes.label: Linear relationship
nodes.title: A relationship between two variables that can be represented by a straight line on a graph and has a constant rate of change.

nodes.label: Tabular representation of linear relationships
nodes.title: Displaying values of variables in a table to show how they change in relation to each other in a linear relationship.

nodes.label: Graphical representation of linear relationships
nodes.title: Plotting points and drawing lines on the Cartesian plane to visually represent linear relationships.

nodes.label: Slope of a line
nodes.title: A measure of the steepness of a line, representing the rate of change between two variables in a linear relationship.

nodes.label: Rate of change
nodes.title: The amount by which one quantity changes with respect to another, equivalent to the slope in linear relationships.

nodes.label: Y-intercept (start value)
nodes.title: The point where a line crosses the y-axis, representing the initial value in a linear relationship.

nodes.label: Point of intersection of two lines
nodes.title: The point on the Cartesian plane where two linear graphs meet, representing the solution to a system of two linear equations.

nodes.label: Comparing linear relationships
nodes.title: Analyzing and contrasting different linear relationships by examining their slopes and y-intercepts.

nodes.label: Solving systems of two linear equations
nodes.title: Finding the solution(s) that satisfy two linear equations simultaneously, often by graphical, numeric, or mental strategies.

nodes.label: Right-angled triangles
nodes.title: Triangles in which one of the angles is exactly 90 degrees.

nodes.label: Pythagoras' theorem
nodes.title: A theorem stating that in a right-angled triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides.

nodes.label: Solving right-angled triangle problems involving heights and distances
nodes.title: Applying geometric and trigonometric methods to find unknown lengths or heights in real-world or mathematical contexts using right-angled triangles.

nodes.label: Trigonometric ratios
nodes.title: Ratios of the lengths of sides in a right-angled triangle, specifically sine, cosine, and tangent.

nodes.label: Solving real world problems involving angles using trigonometric ratios
nodes.title: Applying sine, cosine, and tangent to calculate unknown angles or lengths in practical situations.

nodes.label: Translation
nodes.title: A geometric transformation that slides every point of a shape the same distance in the same direction.

nodes.label: Central Symmetry
nodes.title: A transformation where each point and its image are the same distance from a fixed central point but in opposite directions.

nodes.label: Axial Symmetry
nodes.title: A transformation where a figure is reflected across a line (axis of symmetry), producing a mirror image.

nodes.label: Rotation
nodes.title: A transformation that turns a figure about a fixed point through a specified angle and direction.

nodes.label: Enlargement
nodes.title: A transformation that changes the size of a shape by a scale factor from a center of enlargement.

nodes.label: Centre of Enlargement
nodes.title: The fixed point in the plane from which distances are measured in an enlargement transformation.

nodes.label: Scale Factor (k)
nodes.title: A number that describes how much a figure is enlarged or reduced with respect to the center of enlargement.

nodes.label: Effect of Enlargement on Area
nodes.title: The area of a shape after enlargement changes by the square of the scale factor.

nodes.label: Axis of Symmetry
nodes.title: A line that divides a shape into two mirror-image halves.

nodes.label: Recognising Images under Transformation
nodes.title: Identifying the result of applying a transformation (translation, symmetry, rotation, enlargement) to a point or object.

nodes.label: Solving Problems Involving Enlargements
nodes.title: Applying knowledge of enlargement transformations to solve geometric problems, including finding images, pre-images, scale factors, and centers.

nodes.label: synthetic geometry
nodes.title: A branch of geometry that uses axioms and logical reasoning to study geometric properties without coordinates or formulas.

nodes.label: geometric construction
nodes.title: The process of drawing geometric figures using only a compass and straightedge, following specific steps.

nodes.label: construction 16-21
nodes.title: Specific geometric constructions outlined in the curriculum, such as bisecting angles or constructing perpendiculars.

nodes.label: construction 22
nodes.title: A specific geometric construction task as defined in the curriculum, requiring mastery of previous construction skills.

nodes.label: theorem
nodes.title: A mathematical statement that has been proven to be true using logical reasoning and previously established statements.

nodes.label: proof
nodes.title: A logical argument that demonstrates the truth of a mathematical statement.

nodes.label: axiom
nodes.title: A basic assumption or self-evident truth used as a starting point for further reasoning and arguments.

nodes.label: corollary
nodes.title: A statement that follows readily from a previously proven statement or theorem.

nodes.label: converse
nodes.title: A statement formed by reversing the hypothesis and conclusion of a given conditional statement.

nodes.label: implies
nodes.title: A logical relationship where the truth of one statement guarantees the truth of another.

nodes.label: is equivalent to
nodes.title: A logical relationship where two statements are true or false under the same conditions.

nodes.label: if and only if
nodes.title: A logical connector indicating that both statements are true together or false together; denotes equivalence.

nodes.label: proof by contradiction
nodes.title: A method of proof where the negation of the statement is assumed, leading to a contradiction.

nodes.label: theorems 7, 8, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 20, 21
nodes.title: Specific geometric theorems outlined in the curriculum, covering properties and relationships in geometry.

nodes.label: corollary 6
nodes.title: A specific corollary derived from earlier theorems in the curriculum.

nodes.label: ratios in geometry
nodes.title: The comparison of lengths, areas, or other quantities in geometric figures, often used in similarity and proportionality.

nodes.label: theorem of Pythagoras
nodes.title: A fundamental result in geometry stating that in a right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides.

nodes.label: Parallel Lines
nodes.title: Two lines in a plane that never intersect and have the same slope.

nodes.label: Perpendicular Lines
nodes.title: Two lines that intersect at a right angle (90 degrees), with slopes that are negative reciprocals of each other.

nodes.label: Linear Equation in Two Variables
nodes.title: An equation of the form ax + by + c = 0, representing a straight line in the coordinate plane.

nodes.label: Area of a Triangle (Coordinate Geometry)
nodes.title: The calculation of the area of a triangle given the coordinates of its vertices, often using the determinant formula.

nodes.label: Equation of a Circle (Center (h, k), Radius r)
nodes.title: The equation (x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 = r^2 represents all points (x, y) at a distance r from the center (h, k).

nodes.label: Equation of a Circle (General Form)
nodes.title: The equation x^2 + y^2 + 2gx + 2fy + c = 0 represents a circle with center (-g, -f) and radius sqrt(g^2 + f^2 - c).

nodes.label: Distance from a Point to a Line
nodes.title: The shortest (perpendicular) distance between a given point and a straight line in the plane.

nodes.label: Angle Between Two Lines
nodes.title: The measure of the angle formed where two lines intersect, calculated using their slopes.

nodes.label: Internal Division of a Line Segment
nodes.title: Dividing a line segment into a given ratio m:n internally, finding the coordinates of the dividing point.

nodes.label: Intersection of a Line and a Circle
nodes.title: Solving for the points where a given line and a circle meet in the coordinate plane.

nodes.label: Trigonometric Ratios (sine, cosine, tangent)
nodes.title: Ratios of the sides of a right triangle used to define the sine, cosine, and tangent functions for an angle.

nodes.label: Area of a Triangle using Trigonometry
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a triangle using the formula 1/2 ab sin C, where a and b are sides and C is the included angle.

nodes.label: Sine Rule
nodes.title: A formula relating the lengths of the sides of a triangle to the sines of its angles: a/sinA = b/sinB = c/sinC.

nodes.label: Cosine Rule
nodes.title: A formula that relates the lengths of the sides of a triangle to the cosine of one of its angles: c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab cosC.

nodes.label: Definition of sin θ and cos θ for all values of θ
nodes.title: Extending the definitions of sine and cosine beyond acute angles to all real values of θ, using the unit circle.

nodes.label: Definition of tan θ
nodes.title: Defining the tangent of an angle as the ratio of sine to cosine: tan θ = sin θ / cos θ.

nodes.label: Area of a Sector of a Circle
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a sector using the formula (1/2) r^2 θ, where θ is in radians.

nodes.label: Length of an Arc
nodes.title: Finding the length of an arc of a circle using the formula rθ, where θ is in radians.

nodes.label: Trigonometric Ratios in Surd Form
nodes.title: Expressing trigonometric ratios exactly using surds (irrational roots) rather than decimal approximations.

nodes.label: 3D Trigonometry Problem Solving
nodes.title: Applying trigonometric methods to solve problems involving three-dimensional figures.

nodes.label: Graphing Trigonometric Functions
nodes.title: Plotting the graphs of sine, cosine, and tangent functions over a range of values.

nodes.label: Graphing Transformed Trigonometric Functions
nodes.title: Graphing functions of the form f(θ) = a + b sin(cθ) and g(θ) = a + b cos(cθ) for real values of a, b, c.

nodes.label: Solving Trigonometric Equations
nodes.title: Finding all solutions to equations involving trigonometric functions, such as sin nθ = 0 and cos nθ = 1/2.

nodes.label: Radian Measure of Angles
nodes.title: Measuring angles in radians, where one radian is the angle subtended by an arc equal in length to the radius of the circle.

nodes.label: Derivation of Trigonometric Formulae
nodes.title: Developing trigonometric identities and formulas from first principles or known results.

nodes.label: Application of Trigonometric Formulae
nodes.title: Using established trigonometric identities and formulas to solve mathematical problems.

nodes.label: enlargement (transformation geometry)
nodes.title: A type of transformation that increases or decreases the size of a geometric figure from a fixed point called the centre of enlargement, using a scale factor.

nodes.label: scale factor (k) in enlargement
nodes.title: A multiplier that determines how much a figure is enlarged or reduced in an enlargement transformation; k > 1 for enlargement, 0 < k < 1 for reduction.

nodes.label: rational scale factor
nodes.title: A scale factor for enlargement that is a rational number (k ∈ Q), allowing for precise fractional enlargements or reductions.

nodes.label: Natural numbers (N)
nodes.title: The set of counting numbers starting from 1, i.e., {1, 2, 3, ...}.

nodes.label: Integers (Z)
nodes.title: The set of whole numbers including positive numbers, negative numbers, and zero.

nodes.label: Rational numbers (Q)
nodes.title: Numbers that can be expressed as a fraction a/b, where a and b are integers and b ≠ 0.

nodes.label: Fractions
nodes.title: A representation of rational numbers as the ratio of two integers.

nodes.label: Decimals
nodes.title: A representation of numbers using powers of ten, including finite and repeating decimals for rational numbers.

nodes.label: Percentages
nodes.title: A way of expressing numbers as a fraction of 100.

nodes.label: Addition of natural numbers
nodes.title: Combining two or more natural numbers to find their sum.

nodes.label: Subtraction of natural numbers
nodes.title: Finding the difference between two natural numbers.

nodes.label: Multiplication of natural numbers
nodes.title: Finding the product of two or more natural numbers.

nodes.label: Division of natural numbers
nodes.title: Splitting a natural number into equal groups.

nodes.label: Addition of integers
nodes.title: Combining positive and negative whole numbers, including zero.

nodes.label: Subtraction of integers
nodes.title: Finding the difference between integers, including negative results.

nodes.label: Multiplication of integers
nodes.title: Finding the product of two or more integers, including sign rules.

nodes.label: Division of integers
nodes.title: Dividing one integer by another, including sign rules.

nodes.label: Addition of rational numbers
nodes.title: Combining rational numbers, including fractions and decimals.

nodes.label: Subtraction of rational numbers
nodes.title: Finding the difference between rational numbers.

nodes.label: Multiplication of rational numbers
nodes.title: Finding the product of rational numbers.

nodes.label: Division of rational numbers
nodes.title: Dividing one rational number by another.

nodes.label: Properties of arithmetic operations
nodes.title: Rules governing addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division, such as commutative, associative, and distributive laws.

nodes.label: Commutative law
nodes.title: The order of addition or multiplication does not affect the result.

nodes.label: Associative law
nodes.title: The grouping of numbers in addition or multiplication does not affect the result.

nodes.label: Distributive law
nodes.title: Multiplication distributes over addition or subtraction, e.g., a(b + c) = ab + ac.

nodes.label: Order of operations
nodes.title: The rules that define the sequence in which operations are performed, including the use of brackets.

nodes.label: Number line representation
nodes.title: A visual model for representing numbers and their order, including natural numbers, integers, and rational numbers.

nodes.label: Decomposition (in arithmetic)
nodes.title: Breaking numbers into parts to simplify operations, such as addition or subtraction.

nodes.label: Skip counting
nodes.title: Counting forward or backward by numbers other than one, often used to introduce multiplication.

nodes.label: Arrays (in multiplication)
nodes.title: Arranging objects in rows and columns to model multiplication.

nodes.label: Inverse operations
nodes.title: Operations that undo each other, such as addition and subtraction or multiplication and division.

nodes.label: Contextual problem solving with numbers
nodes.title: Applying arithmetic operations to real-life situations and interpreting results.

nodes.label: Negative numbers in context
nodes.title: Interpreting negative numbers in real-world situations, such as debts or temperatures below zero.

nodes.label: Fractional amounts in context
nodes.title: Solving problems involving parts of a whole in real-life scenarios.

nodes.label: Irrational Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers that cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers; their decimal expansions are non-terminating and non-repeating.

nodes.label: Real Numbers (R)
nodes.title: The set of numbers including both rational and irrational numbers.

nodes.label: Complex Numbers (C)
nodes.title: Numbers of the form a + ib, where a and b are real numbers and i is the imaginary unit.

nodes.label: Addition in Number Systems
nodes.title: The operation of combining two numbers to get their sum, applied within different number domains.

nodes.label: Subtraction in Number Systems
nodes.title: The operation of finding the difference between two numbers, within various number domains.

nodes.label: Multiplication in Number Systems
nodes.title: The operation of repeated addition of a number, within various number domains.

nodes.label: Division in Number Systems
nodes.title: The operation of distributing a number into equal parts, within various number domains.

nodes.label: Rectangular Form of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Expressing complex numbers as a + ib, where a is the real part and b is the imaginary part.

nodes.label: Argand Diagram
nodes.title: A graphical representation of complex numbers on a plane, with the real part on the x-axis and the imaginary part on the y-axis.

nodes.label: Modulus of a Complex Number
nodes.title: The distance of a complex number from the origin in the Argand diagram, calculated as sqrt(a^2 + b^2) for a + ib.

nodes.label: Complex Conjugate
nodes.title: For a complex number a + ib, the complex conjugate is a - ib.

nodes.label: Decimals as Equivalent Fractions
nodes.title: Understanding decimals as special cases of fractions and relating them to place value.

nodes.label: Factors
nodes.title: Numbers that divide another number exactly without leaving a remainder.

nodes.label: Multiples
nodes.title: Numbers that are the product of a given number and an integer.

nodes.label: Prime Numbers
nodes.title: Natural numbers greater than 1 that have no positive divisors other than 1 and itself.

nodes.label: Prime Factorization
nodes.title: Expressing a number as a product of its prime factors.

nodes.label: Scientific Notation
nodes.title: Expressing numbers in the form a × 10^n, where 1 ≤ a < 10 and n is an integer.

nodes.label: Geometric Construction of Square Roots
nodes.title: Using geometric methods to construct values like √2 and √3.

nodes.label: Proof of Irrationality
nodes.title: Demonstrating that certain numbers, such as √2, cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers.

nodes.label: Complex Conjugate of Sums and Products
nodes.title: Calculating the conjugate of the sum or product of two complex numbers.

nodes.label: Number Patterns and Formulae
nodes.title: Identifying, verifying, and justifying patterns and formulae in sequences of numbers.

nodes.label: Geometric Sequences and Series
nodes.title: Sequences where each term is found by multiplying the previous term by a constant ratio; includes finite and infinite series.

nodes.label: Mathematical Induction
nodes.title: A proof technique used to establish the validity of statements for all natural numbers.

nodes.label: Sum of First n Natural Numbers
nodes.title: The formula for the sum of the first n natural numbers: n(n+1)/2.

nodes.label: Sum of a Finite Geometric Series
nodes.title: The formula to sum the terms of a finite geometric sequence.

nodes.label: Inequalities Involving Factorials and Exponents
nodes.title: Proving inequalities such as n! > 2^n, 2^n ≥ n^2 (for n ≥ 4), and (1+x)^n ≥ 1+nx (for x > -1).

nodes.label: Factorization Results
nodes.title: Proving divisibility results, such as 3 is a factor of 4^n – 1.

nodes.label: Limits of Sequences
nodes.title: Finding the value that a sequence approaches as the index goes to infinity.

nodes.label: Rules for Sums, Products, and Quotients of Limits
nodes.title: Applying limit laws to combine limits of sequences or functions.

nodes.label: Limit of a Geometric Sequence
nodes.title: Determining the limit of a sequence of the form r^n as n approaches infinity.

nodes.label: Sum to Infinity of a Geometric Series
nodes.title: Deriving and applying the formula for the sum to infinity of a geometric series when the common ratio's absolute value is less than one.

nodes.label: Recurring Decimals as Infinite Geometric Series
nodes.title: Expressing recurring decimals as the sum of an infinite geometric series.

nodes.label: Financial Applications of Geometric Series
nodes.title: Applying geometric series to solve problems such as mortgage repayments and other financial calculations.

nodes.label: Equality as a relationship
nodes.title: Understanding that equality means two mathematical expressions have the same value.

nodes.label: Analyzing solution strategies
nodes.title: Evaluating and comparing different methods for solving mathematical problems.

nodes.label: Calculating percentages
nodes.title: Finding a percentage of a quantity or expressing a number as a percentage.

nodes.label: Equivalence of fractions, decimals, and percentages
nodes.title: Recognizing and converting between fractions, decimals, and percentages to compare proportions.

nodes.label: Comparing proportions
nodes.title: Assessing the relative sizes of quantities using fractions, decimals, or percentages.

nodes.label: Prime numbers in N
nodes.title: Natural numbers greater than 1 that have no positive divisors other than 1 and themselves.

nodes.label: Relationship between ratio and proportion
nodes.title: Understanding how ratios compare quantities and how proportions show equality between ratios.

nodes.label: Checking results by order of magnitude
nodes.title: Verifying the plausibility of an answer by considering its scale or size.

nodes.label: Checking results by working backwards
nodes.title: Validating a solution by reversing the steps of the calculation.

nodes.label: Rounding off results
nodes.title: Adjusting a number to a specified degree of accuracy, such as to the nearest whole number or decimal place.

nodes.label: Estimation and approximation of calculations
nodes.title: Making reasonable guesses or simplified calculations to check or predict results.

nodes.label: Presenting numerical answers to specified accuracy
nodes.title: Expressing answers with the required number of decimal places or significant figures.

nodes.label: Expressing non-zero positive rational numbers in standard form
nodes.title: Writing numbers in the form a × 10ⁿ, where 1 ≤ a < 10 and n is an integer.

nodes.label: Square Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers obtained by multiplying an integer by itself (e.g., 4 = 2 × 2).

nodes.label: Cube Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers obtained by multiplying an integer by itself twice (e.g., 8 = 2 × 2 × 2).

nodes.label: Square Roots
nodes.title: The value that, when multiplied by itself, gives the original number (e.g., √9 = 3).

nodes.label: Reciprocals
nodes.title: The multiplicative inverse of a number; for a nonzero number a, its reciprocal is 1/a.

nodes.label: Index Notation
nodes.title: A way of expressing repeated multiplication of the same number using exponents (e.g., a^n).

nodes.label: Contextual Problem Solving with Indices
nodes.title: Applying knowledge of indices, roots, and reciprocals to solve real-world or word problems.

nodes.label: number sequences
nodes.title: An ordered list of numbers generated by a specific process or rule.

nodes.label: pattern recognition in sequences
nodes.title: Identifying regularities or rules that govern the formation of a sequence.

nodes.label: extending sequences
nodes.title: Using identified patterns to continue a sequence beyond the given terms.

nodes.label: generalising patterns
nodes.title: Expressing the rule of a pattern or sequence in a general or algebraic form.

nodes.label: algebraic representation of sequences
nodes.title: Using algebraic expressions or formulas to describe the nth term or rule of a sequence.

nodes.label: arithmetic sequence
nodes.title: A sequence of numbers in which the difference between consecutive terms is constant.

nodes.label: geometric sequence
nodes.title: A sequence of numbers in which each term after the first is found by multiplying the previous term by a fixed, non-zero number called the common ratio.

nodes.label: identifying sequence types
nodes.title: Determining whether a given sequence is arithmetic, geometric, or neither.

nodes.label: sum to n terms of an arithmetic series
nodes.title: Calculating the sum of the first n terms of an arithmetic sequence using a formula.

nodes.label: Laws of indices
nodes.title: Rules governing the manipulation of expressions involving exponents, such as product, quotient, and power rules.

nodes.label: Product of powers rule
nodes.title: The rule that states a^p * a^q = a^(p+q) for the same base a.

nodes.label: Quotient of powers rule
nodes.title: The rule that states a^p / a^q = a^(p-q) for the same base a.

nodes.label: Zero index rule
nodes.title: The rule that any nonzero number raised to the power of zero equals one: a^0 = 1.

nodes.label: Power of a power rule
nodes.title: The rule that (a^p)^q = a^(pq).

nodes.label: Negative index rule
nodes.title: The rule that a^(-p) = 1 / a^p.

nodes.label: Fractional indices
nodes.title: Indices that are fractions, representing roots, such as a^(1/q) = qth root of a.

nodes.label: Product to a power rule
nodes.title: The rule that (ab)^p = a^p * b^p.

nodes.label: Quotient to a power rule
nodes.title: The rule that (a/b)^p = a^p / b^p.

nodes.label: Logarithms
nodes.title: The inverse operation to exponentiation, relating exponents to multiplication.

nodes.label: Laws of logarithms
nodes.title: Rules for manipulating logarithmic expressions, such as product, quotient, and power rules.

nodes.label: Product rule for logarithms
nodes.title: The rule that log_a(xy) = log_a(x) + log_a(y).

nodes.label: Quotient rule for logarithms
nodes.title: The rule that log_a(x/y) = log_a(x) - log_a(y).

nodes.label: Power rule for logarithms
nodes.title: The rule that log_a(x^q) = q * log_a(x).

nodes.label: Logarithm of base
nodes.title: The rule that log_a(a) = 1.

nodes.label: Logarithm of one
nodes.title: The rule that log_a(1) = 0.

nodes.label: Change of base formula for logarithms
nodes.title: The formula log_a(x) = log_b(x) / log_b(a), allowing logarithms to be converted between different bases.

nodes.label: sequence generation
nodes.title: The process of creating a list of numbers or objects following a specific rule or pattern.

nodes.label: generalising patterns in algebraic form
nodes.title: Expressing the rule or relationship of a sequence using algebraic expressions or formulas.

nodes.label: classification of sequences
nodes.title: Determining whether a sequence is arithmetic, geometric, or neither based on its pattern.

nodes.label: Product rule for indices
nodes.title: The rule stating that when multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents: a^p * a^q = a^{p+q}.

nodes.label: Quotient rule for indices
nodes.title: The rule stating that when dividing powers with the same base, subtract the exponents: a^p / a^q = a^{p-q}.

nodes.label: Fractional index rule
nodes.title: The rule stating that a^{1/q} = qth root of a, and a^{p/q} = (qth root of a)^p.

nodes.label: Product of powers with different bases
nodes.title: The rule stating that (ab)^p = a^p * b^p.

nodes.label: Quotient of powers with different bases
nodes.title: The rule stating that (a/b)^p = a^p / b^p.

nodes.label: Logarithm laws
nodes.title: Rules governing the manipulation of logarithms, including product, quotient, and power rules.

nodes.label: Solving problems using indices and logarithms
nodes.title: Applying the rules of indices and logarithms to solve mathematical problems.
nodes.broader_concept: Problem Solving with Exponents and Logarithms

nodes.label: profit and loss calculation
nodes.title: Finding the amount of profit or loss made in a transaction, typically by comparing selling price and cost price.

nodes.label: percentage profit and loss
nodes.title: Calculating profit or loss as a percentage of the cost price.

nodes.label: discount calculation
nodes.title: Determining the reduction in price, often expressed as a percentage of the original price.

nodes.label: percentage discount
nodes.title: Calculating the discount as a percentage of the original price.

nodes.label: selling price determination
nodes.title: Finding the final price at which an item is sold after applying discounts or adding profit.

nodes.label: compound interest calculation (up to 3 years)
nodes.title: Calculating the total amount and interest earned on a principal over up to 3 years, where interest is added to the principal each period.

nodes.label: income tax calculation (standard rate)
nodes.title: Computing the amount of income tax owed using a standard tax rate.

nodes.label: net pay calculation with deductions
nodes.title: Determining take-home pay after subtracting income tax and other specified deductions from gross pay.

nodes.label: value for money analysis
nodes.title: Comparing the cost and benefits of different products or services to determine the best value.

nodes.label: ratio and proportion
nodes.title: Using ratios and proportions to solve problems involving relative sizes and scaling.

nodes.label: currency conversion
nodes.title: Converting amounts between different currencies using exchange rates.

nodes.label: unit conversion (measure and time)
nodes.title: Changing quantities from one unit to another, such as meters to kilometers or minutes to hours.

nodes.label: meter reading interpretation
nodes.title: Reading and interpreting values from utility meters (e.g., electricity, water, gas) to calculate usage.

nodes.label: timetable interpretation
nodes.title: Reading and using information from timetables to plan journeys or schedules.

nodes.label: average speed calculation
nodes.title: Finding the average speed by dividing total distance by total time taken.

nodes.label: distance calculation using speed and time
nodes.title: Calculating distance traveled using the formula distance = speed × time.

nodes.label: time calculation using speed and distance
nodes.title: Finding the time taken for a journey using the formula time = distance ÷ speed.

nodes.label: VAT calculation
nodes.title: Calculating the value-added tax on goods and services, often as a percentage of the price.

nodes.label: mobile phone tariff comparison
nodes.title: Comparing different mobile phone plans to determine the most cost-effective option.

nodes.label: 2D shapes
nodes.title: Flat figures with two dimensions, such as squares, rectangles, triangles, and circles.

nodes.label: 3D solids
nodes.title: Three-dimensional objects such as cubes, rectangular prisms, cylinders, and spheres.

nodes.label: nets of solids
nodes.title: Two-dimensional patterns that can be folded to form three-dimensional solids.

nodes.label: surface area
nodes.title: The total area of all the surfaces of a three-dimensional object.

nodes.label: volume
nodes.title: The amount of space occupied by a three-dimensional object.

nodes.label: perimeter
nodes.title: The total length around a two-dimensional shape.

nodes.label: modelling real-world situations
nodes.title: Applying mathematical concepts to represent and solve problems from everyday contexts.

nodes.label: multi-step problem solving
nodes.title: Solving problems that require more than one operation or step.

nodes.label: area of a disc
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a circle using the formula A = πr².

nodes.label: area of a triangle
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a triangle using the formula A = ½bh.

nodes.label: area of a rectangle
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a rectangle using the formula A = lw.

nodes.label: area of a square
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a square using the formula A = s².

nodes.label: area of composite shapes
nodes.title: Finding the area of shapes made by combining regular and irregular figures.

nodes.label: volume of rectangular solids
nodes.title: Calculating the volume of cuboids using the formula V = lwh.

nodes.label: volume of cylinders
nodes.title: Calculating the volume of a cylinder using the formula V = πr²h.

nodes.label: volume of spheres
nodes.title: Calculating the volume of a sphere using the formula V = 4/3πr³.

nodes.label: surface area of rectangular solids
nodes.title: Calculating the total surface area of cuboids using the formula SA = 2(lw + lh + wh).

nodes.label: surface area of cylinders
nodes.title: Calculating the surface area of a cylinder using the formula SA = 2πr(h + r).

nodes.label: surface area of spheres
nodes.title: Calculating the surface area of a sphere using the formula SA = 4πr².

nodes.label: circumference of a circle
nodes.title: The distance around a circle, calculated using C = 2πr or C = πd.

nodes.label: relationship between circumference, diameter, and pi
nodes.title: Understanding that the circumference of a circle is equal to pi times its diameter.

nodes.label: scaled diagrams
nodes.title: Drawing and interpreting diagrams where dimensions are proportionally reduced or enlarged.

nodes.label: estimation of area
nodes.title: Using strategies to approximate the area of regular and irregular shapes.

nodes.label: Order of Magnitude Estimation
nodes.title: Assessing whether a numerical result is reasonable by comparing it to an expected scale or size.

nodes.label: Reverse Calculation (Checking by Working Backwards)
nodes.title: Verifying a result by performing the inverse operations to see if the original value is obtained.

nodes.label: Rounding Off
nodes.title: Adjusting a numerical value to a specified degree of accuracy, such as to the nearest whole number or decimal place.

nodes.label: Error Accumulation (Addition and Subtraction)
nodes.title: Calculating how measurement or rounding errors combine when quantities are added or subtracted.

nodes.label: Percentage Error
nodes.title: Calculating the difference between an approximate and exact value as a percentage of the exact value.

nodes.label: Tolerance
nodes.title: The allowable variation in a measured or calculated value, often expressed as a range or percentage.

nodes.label: Average Rate of Change (with respect to time)
nodes.title: Calculating the change in a quantity divided by the time taken for that change.

nodes.label: Cost Price Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the original price paid to produce or purchase an item.

nodes.label: Selling Price Calculation
nodes.title: Calculating the price at which an item is sold to customers.

nodes.label: Loss Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the amount lost when the selling price is less than the cost price.

nodes.label: Mark Up (Profit as a Percentage of Cost Price)
nodes.title: Calculating the profit as a percentage of the cost price added to determine the selling price.

nodes.label: Margin (Profit as a Percentage of Selling Price)
nodes.title: Calculating the profit as a percentage of the selling price.

nodes.label: Compound Interest Calculation
nodes.title: Calculating interest on both the initial principal and the accumulated interest from previous periods.

nodes.label: Depreciation (Reducing Balance Method)
nodes.title: Calculating the decrease in value of an asset by applying a fixed percentage reduction to its book value each period.

nodes.label: Income Tax Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the amount of tax owed based on income and applicable tax rates.

nodes.label: Net Pay Calculation (Including Deductions)
nodes.title: Calculating the amount received after subtracting taxes and other deductions from gross income.

nodes.label: Costing: Materials, Labour, and Wastage
nodes.title: Calculating the total cost of production by considering material costs, labor costs, and losses due to wastage.

nodes.label: Metric System
nodes.title: A decimal-based system of measurement used internationally, including units such as meters, liters, and grams.

nodes.label: Unit Conversion (Metric and Imperial)
nodes.title: Changing a measurement from one unit to another, including between metric and imperial systems.

nodes.label: Estimation of Physical Measures
nodes.title: Making reasonable guesses of measurements (such as length, mass, or volume) in real-world contexts.

nodes.label: Present Value Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the current worth of a future sum of money or stream of cash flows given a specified rate of return.

nodes.label: nets of prisms
nodes.title: A net is a two-dimensional pattern that can be folded to form a three-dimensional prism.

nodes.label: nets of cylinders
nodes.title: A net is a two-dimensional pattern that can be folded to form a cylinder.

nodes.label: nets of cones
nodes.title: A net is a two-dimensional pattern that can be folded to form a cone.

nodes.label: perimeter of plane figures
nodes.title: The total length around the boundary of a two-dimensional shape.

nodes.label: area of a parallelogram
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a parallelogram, calculated as base × height.

nodes.label: area of a trapezium
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a trapezium, calculated as ½ × (sum of parallel sides) × height.

nodes.label: area of a sector of a disc
nodes.title: The area of a portion of a circle, calculated as (θ/360) × πr² for angle θ.

nodes.label: area of composite figures
nodes.title: Finding the area of shapes made by combining two or more basic shapes.

nodes.label: surface area of a rectangular block
nodes.title: The total area of all the faces of a rectangular prism.

nodes.label: surface area of a cylinder
nodes.title: The total area of the curved surface and the two bases of a cylinder.

nodes.label: surface area of a right cone
nodes.title: The total area of the curved surface and the base of a right circular cone.

nodes.label: surface area of a triangular-based prism
nodes.title: The total area of all faces of a prism with a triangular base.

nodes.label: surface area of a sphere
nodes.title: The total area covering the surface of a sphere, calculated as 4πr².

nodes.label: surface area of a hemisphere
nodes.title: The total area covering the curved surface and the base of a hemisphere.

nodes.label: surface area of composite solids
nodes.title: Finding the surface area of solids made by combining two or more basic solids.

nodes.label: volume of a rectangular block
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a rectangular prism, calculated as length × width × height.

nodes.label: volume of a cylinder
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a cylinder, calculated as πr²h.

nodes.label: volume of a right cone
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a right circular cone, calculated as (1/3)πr²h.

nodes.label: volume of a triangular-based prism
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a prism with a triangular base, calculated as area of base × height.

nodes.label: volume of a sphere
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a sphere, calculated as (4/3)πr³.

nodes.label: volume of a hemisphere
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a hemisphere, calculated as (2/3)πr³.

nodes.label: volume of composite solids
nodes.title: Finding the volume of solids made by combining two or more basic solids.

nodes.label: trapezoidal rule
nodes.title: A numerical method for approximating the area under a curve by dividing it into trapezoids.

nodes.label: Surds
nodes.title: Irrational roots that cannot be simplified to remove the root symbol (e.g., √2, √3).

nodes.label: Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers of the form a + bi, where a and b are real numbers and i is the imaginary unit.

nodes.label: Imaginary Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers involving the square root of negative numbers, typically written as bi.

nodes.label: Addition and Subtraction of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Combining complex numbers by adding or subtracting their real and imaginary parts separately.

nodes.label: Multiplication of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Multiplying complex numbers using distributive property and i^2 = -1.

nodes.label: Division of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Dividing complex numbers by multiplying numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator.

nodes.label: Equality of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Two complex numbers are equal if their real and imaginary parts are equal.

nodes.label: Transformations of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Operations such as translation, rotation, reflection, and dilation applied to complex numbers in the complex plane.

nodes.label: Conjugate Roots Theorem
nodes.title: If a polynomial with real coefficients has a complex root, its complex conjugate is also a root.

nodes.label: Polar Form of a Complex Number
nodes.title: Expressing a complex number as r(cos θ + i sin θ), where r is the modulus and θ is the argument.

nodes.label: Products and Quotients in Polar Form
nodes.title: Multiplying and dividing complex numbers in polar form by multiplying/dividing moduli and adding/subtracting arguments.
nodes.broader_concept: Polar Form of a Complex Number

nodes.label: De Moivre's Theorem
nodes.title: For any real θ and integer n, (cos θ + i sin θ)^n = cos(nθ) + i sin(nθ).

nodes.label: Finding nth Roots of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Using De Moivre's theorem to find all nth roots of a complex number in polar form.

nodes.label: Enlargement (Dilation)
nodes.title: A transformation that increases or decreases the size of a figure by a scale factor from a fixed point (centre of enlargement).

nodes.label: Scale Factor
nodes.title: The ratio of any two corresponding lengths in two similar geometric figures.

nodes.label: Area Scale Factor
nodes.title: In similar figures, the ratio of areas is the square of the scale factor.

nodes.label: Constructions with Compass and Straightedge
nodes.title: Classical geometric constructions such as bisecting lines and angles, constructing perpendiculars, and drawing circles.

nodes.label: Circumcircle of a Triangle
nodes.title: A circle passing through all three vertices of a triangle; its centre is the intersection of the perpendicular bisectors of the sides.

nodes.label: Incircle of a Triangle
nodes.title: A circle inscribed in a triangle, tangent to all three sides; its centre is the intersection of the angle bisectors.

nodes.label: Centroid of a Triangle
nodes.title: The point of intersection of the medians of a triangle; it is the triangle's centre of mass.

nodes.label: Orthocentre of a Triangle
nodes.title: The point where the three altitudes of a triangle intersect.

nodes.label: Antidifferentiation (Indefinite Integration)
nodes.title: The process of finding a function whose derivative is a given function.

nodes.label: Definite Integral
nodes.title: The evaluation of the integral of a function between two limits, giving the net area under the curve.

nodes.label: Integration of Exponential Functions
nodes.title: Finding antiderivatives of functions involving exponents, such as e^x and a^x.

nodes.label: Integration of Trigonometric Functions
nodes.title: Finding antiderivatives of functions like sin(ax), cos(ax), etc.

nodes.label: Area Under a Curve by Integration
nodes.title: Using definite integrals to calculate the area between a function and the x-axis.

nodes.label: Area Between Two Curves
nodes.title: Finding the area enclosed between two functions by integrating their difference.

nodes.label: Average Value of a Function
nodes.title: The mean height of a function over an interval, calculated as (1/(b-a))∫_a^b f(x) dx.

nodes.label: Chain Rule for Differentiation
nodes.title: A rule for finding the derivative of a composite function.

nodes.label: Product Rule for Differentiation
nodes.title: A rule for differentiating the product of two functions.

nodes.label: Quotient Rule for Differentiation
nodes.title: A rule for differentiating the quotient of two functions.

nodes.label: Stationary Points
nodes.title: Points on a curve where the derivative is zero; includes maxima, minima, and points of inflection.

nodes.label: Second Derivative Test
nodes.title: A method for determining the nature (maximum or minimum) of a stationary point using the second derivative.

nodes.label: Point of Inflection
nodes.title: A point on a curve where the concavity changes; second derivative is zero and changes sign.

nodes.label: Slope Function (Derived Function)
nodes.title: The function representing the derivative (rate of change) of another function.

nodes.label: Maximum and Minimum Problems (Optimization)
nodes.title: Using calculus to find the maximum or minimum values of a function, often in applied contexts.

nodes.label: Rates of Change
nodes.title: How a quantity changes with respect to another, often time; represented by derivatives.

nodes.label: Related Rates of Change
nodes.title: Problems involving two or more quantities that change with respect to time and are related by an equation.

nodes.label: Compound Interest
nodes.title: Interest calculated on the initial principal and also on the accumulated interest from previous periods.

nodes.label: Present Value
nodes.title: The current worth of a future sum of money given a specified rate of return.

nodes.label: Instalment Savings (Annuities)
nodes.title: A sequence of equal payments made at regular intervals, with interest compounded at each interval.

nodes.label: Pension Fund Present Value
nodes.title: The amount that must be invested now to provide a fixed pension over a number of years.

nodes.label: Loan and Mortgage Repayments
nodes.title: Calculating regular payments to repay a loan or mortgage over a fixed period at a given interest rate.

nodes.label: Probability Tree Diagrams
nodes.title: A branching diagram representing all possible outcomes of a sequence of events and their probabilities.

nodes.label: Probability Distributions
nodes.title: A function or table that gives the probabilities of occurrence of different possible outcomes.

nodes.label: Expected Value
nodes.title: The mean value of a random variable, calculated as the sum of all possible values weighted by their probabilities.

nodes.label: Bernoulli Trials
nodes.title: A sequence of independent experiments where each has only two possible outcomes (success/failure) and constant probability of success.

nodes.label: Binomial Distribution
nodes.title: The probability distribution of the number of successes in a fixed number of independent Bernoulli trials.

nodes.label: Multiplication Rule for Independent Events
nodes.title: The probability of two independent events both occurring is the product of their probabilities.

nodes.label: Permutations and Combinations in Probability
nodes.title: Counting methods used to determine the number of possible outcomes or arrangements in probability problems.

nodes.label: Probability Simulations
nodes.title: Using random processes (e.g., dice, spinners, random numbers) to model and estimate probabilities.

nodes.label: Functions (Mappings)
nodes.title: A relation in which each input is associated with exactly one output.

nodes.label: Domain and Range of Functions
nodes.title: The set of possible input values (domain) and output values (range) for a function.

nodes.label: Vertical Line Test
nodes.title: A graphical method to determine if a relation is a function.

nodes.label: Composition of Functions
nodes.title: Applying one function to the result of another function.

nodes.label: Injective, Surjective, and Bijective Functions
nodes.title: Types of functions: injective (one-to-one), surjective (onto), bijective (both).

nodes.label: Inverse Functions
nodes.title: A function that 'reverses' another function, mapping outputs back to inputs.

nodes.label: Sketching Graphs of Functions
nodes.title: Drawing rough graphs of functions by identifying key features such as intercepts and turning points.

nodes.label: Quadratic Functions and Their Graphs
nodes.title: Functions of the form ax^2 + bx + c and their parabolic graphs.

nodes.label: Cubic Functions and Their Graphs
nodes.title: Functions of the form ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d and their characteristic S-shaped graphs.

nodes.label: Transformations of Graphs
nodes.title: Shifting, reflecting, stretching, or compressing the graphs of functions.

nodes.label: Exponential Functions
nodes.title: Functions of the form f(x) = a^x, where a > 0 and a ≠ 1.

nodes.label: Logarithmic Functions
nodes.title: The inverse functions of exponential functions, of the form f(x) = log_a(x).

nodes.label: Scatter Diagrams
nodes.title: Graphs showing the relationship between two variables using plotted points.

nodes.label: Correlation
nodes.title: A measure of the strength and direction of a linear relationship between two variables.

nodes.label: Correlation Coefficient (r)
nodes.title: A numerical value between -1 and 1 that quantifies the strength of linear correlation.

nodes.label: Line of Best Fit
nodes.title: A straight line drawn through a scatter diagram to best represent the data trend.

nodes.label: Normal Distribution
nodes.title: A continuous, symmetric, bell-shaped distribution defined by its mean and standard deviation.

nodes.label: Empirical Rule
nodes.title: In a normal distribution, about 68% of values lie within 1 SD, 95% within 2 SD, and 99.7% within 3 SD of the mean.

nodes.label: Standard Score (z-score)
nodes.title: A measure of how many standard deviations a value is from the mean.

nodes.label: Standard Normal Distribution
nodes.title: A normal distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation 1.

nodes.label: Confidence Interval for Population Proportion
nodes.title: An interval estimate for a population proportion, based on a sample proportion and margin of error.

nodes.label: Margin of Error
nodes.title: A measure of the uncertainty in an estimate, often used in confidence intervals.

nodes.label: Standard Error
nodes.title: The standard deviation of a sampling distribution, used to measure variability of sample statistics.

nodes.label: Sampling Distribution of the Mean
nodes.title: The probability distribution of sample means over repeated sampling from a population.

nodes.label: Central Limit Theorem
nodes.title: States that the sampling distribution of the mean approaches normality as sample size increases, regardless of population distribution.

nodes.label: Confidence Interval for Population Mean
nodes.title: An interval estimate for the population mean based on the sample mean and standard error.

nodes.label: Hypothesis Testing for Population Proportion
nodes.title: A statistical procedure to test claims about a population proportion using sample data.

nodes.label: Hypothesis Testing for Population Mean
nodes.title: A statistical procedure to test claims about a population mean using sample data.

nodes.label: Null Hypothesis (H0)
nodes.title: The default assumption that there is no effect or difference in a statistical test.

nodes.label: Alternative Hypothesis (H1)
nodes.title: The hypothesis that there is an effect or difference, contrary to the null hypothesis.

nodes.label: Significance Level (α)
nodes.title: The probability threshold below which the null hypothesis is rejected in a hypothesis test.

nodes.label: Critical Region
nodes.title: The set of values for the test statistic that leads to rejection of the null hypothesis.

nodes.label: p-value
nodes.title: The probability, under the null hypothesis, of obtaining a result as extreme as or more extreme than the observed result.
